{"tid":2110261,"cid":5,"subCid":11,"title":"因為國安法 VPN供應商開始撤離香港","createTime":"2020-07-15T19:34:53.000Z","updateTime":"2020-07-16T18:24:57.000Z","uid":28114,"like":35,"dislike":0,"uniUserReply":15,"replies":[{"pid":"81b71763f6f1e400bbb598cbb72bcc3d30d48b93","tid":2110261,"uid":28114,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-07-15T19:34:53.000Z","msg":"VPN Providers Disable Servers in Hong Kong to Protect Users from China's Security Law<br />\n<br />\nPrivate Internet Access and TunnelBear fear their VPN servers could be confiscated in the event Chinese authorities use the new law to seize them.<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://www.pcmag.com/news/vpn-providers-disable-servers-in-hong-kong-to-protect-users-from-chinas?\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pcmag.com%2Fnews%2Fvpn-providers-disable-servers-in-hong-kong-to-protect-users-from-chinas%3F&d=CgM6%2BPDcwTI4Uk%2BisK9n3z%2BdFj26OgxneTHruUJDv9o%3D&h=5645f661\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.pcmag.com/news/vpn-providers-disable-servers-in-hong-kong-to-protect-users-from-chinas?</a><br />\n<br />\nCiting users&rsquo; safety, two VPN providers are shutting down their servers in Hong Kong in response to China&rsquo;s new security law for the city. <br />\n<br />\nBoth Private Internet Access and TunnelBear have decided to pull the plug on the Hong Kong-based VPN servers over fears local authorities will try to confiscate them. &ldquo;China&rsquo;s new national security law allows law enforcement to seize servers located in Hong Kong without a warrant and otherwise execute warrantless interception of communications,&rdquo; Private Internet Access wrote in a blog post on Tuesday. <br />\n<br />\nThe company&rsquo;s VPN servers collect no logs on user activity. Nevertheless, Private Internet Access indicated it was taking a stand for digital privacy. <br />\n<br />\nTunnelBear also said it stores no users&rsquo; personal identifiable information over the servers. &ldquo;If the server is physically confiscated, and the hard drive is taken out for analysis, the entire hard drive is encrypted,&rdquo; the company wrote in a Monday blog post. The only sensitive information stored over the machines are &ldquo;configuration related keys,&rdquo; which TunnelBear wants to protect."},{"pid":"3d967390d1be5cb2a306e019bf4071a10d0e194e","tid":2110261,"uid":28114,"like":7,"dislike":0,"score":7,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-07-15T19:35:30.000Z","msg":"Hong Kong-based users will still be able to connect to both VPN services. In TunnelBear's case, the provider is scaling up its VPN operations in Singapore and Japan to offset the loss of the Hong Kong server.<br />\n<br />\n&ldquo;We will reinstate the Hong Kong server if and only if our users&rsquo; privacy and safety will be protected,&rdquo; it added. <br />\n<br />\nUnder China&rsquo;s new security law for Hong Kong, local authorities now have broad powers to crack down on political dissent in the city, and jail activists with life imprisonment. According to the BBC, people suspected of breaking the law can also be wire-tapped and put under surveillance. <br />\n<br />\nAs a result, Hong Kong internet users have been flocking to VPN services to protect their digital privacy. However, many residents have been engaging in self-censorship, and purging past statements they've made on social media on fears Chinese authorities will use the content to one day prosecute them.<br />\n<br />\nFor now, US companies including Facebook and Twitter are hitting pause on responding to data requests from Hong Kong law enforcement. <br />\n<br />\nUPDATE 7/15/20: NordVPN said it's keeping the company's VPN servers in Hong Kong online.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;At the moment there is nothing indicating that our users are in any danger. All of our servers are either diskless or encrypted, so even a physical takeover wouldn&rsquo;t compromise our users&rsquo; privacy,&quot; NordVPN said. &quot;Our customers expect accessibility and freedom, and we are not going to restrict them without a good reason. NordVPN is the VPN of choice in Hong Kong, so we address the issue with the utmost responsibility.&quot;<br />\n<br />\nThe company also has a policy against logging users' identifiable information over its servers."},{"pid":"84d530fcb2a53b4c7d5880224ba84873f11af5fa","tid":2110261,"uid":28114,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":1,"replyTime":"2020-07-15T19:36:27.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/shocking.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/shocking.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/shocking.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/shocking.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/shocking.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/shocking.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><br />\n<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/yipes.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/yipes.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/yipes.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/yipes.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/yipes.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/yipes.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><br />\n<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/@.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/@.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/@.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/@.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/@.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/@.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"747bb79dca6bcaedb4c71e92a2929a2c762d5ff6","tid":2110261,"uid":292007,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2020-07-15T19:42:25.000Z","msg":"港區国安法..... <br />\n我都講到悶<br />\n點解仲唔拉人<img src=\"/assets/faces/pig/whip_special.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"caa3006381babf9c209eb9780f288d6cf0e21807","tid":2110261,"uid":28114,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0